MA signs new law (https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/472271-mass-governor-signs-groundbreaking-vaping-flavor-ban-into-law) that restricts the sale of all flavored nicotine vaping products and bans menthol cigarettes as of June 1. Flavored vaping products can be sold and consumed in licensed smoking bars. (Imagine the cost of that license!) Also includes a 75% tax on e-cigarettes and health insurers have to cover tobacco cessation programs. I suspect other States may watch this as a potential model to copy or avoid.

Increasing the probability of bins 2, 3, and 4 in light of news that the AMA is pushing to “ban the sale and distribution of all e-cigarette and vaping products, with the exception of those approved by the F.D.A. for tobacco cessation purposes and made available by prescription only" - this would, in effect, be a full ban on retail sales of vaping products since "no vaping product currently on the market has been approved by the F.D.A. as a 'smoking cessation' device" [2]. I find this development very surprising given that a recent report by the CDC indicates that vaping products specifically containing vitamin E acetate are likely cause of the vaping-related illnesses/deaths nationwide [3] - however, this nevertheless does increase the likelihood of outright state bans on retail sales of all vaping products.

Between 4 October 2019 and 12 May 2020, how many states will fully ban the retail sale of vaping products? Hattip to @JC4841 for analysis showing that conditions change in light of new unexpected information.

Updating in light of a new report out today by the CDC [1] that indicates that vitamin E acetate, which is mostly found in illicit THC vaping substances (see my previous post), is probably the cause of vaping-related illnesses. This probably means that states are extremely unlikely to impose outright bans going forward, especially in light of the fact that none other than MA (a judge has already partly lifted this state's ban) have so far in the time where we have been unsure of the cause. More targeted bans are far more likely than all-encompassing bans now that we know the apparent cause.

Decreasing the probability of bin 1 and increasing that of bins 2 and 3 given recent news that China, "citing health concerns for minors," is banning online sale of e-cigarettes [1]. I am surprised by this development, especially given that the CDC in the US has found that it is specifically THC-containing products that seem to have caused the vast majority of vaping-related illnesses [2]. Nevertheless, because of this recent ban by China, I find it more likely that more U.S. states will ban the retail sale of vaping products but I still think that such outright bans are very unlikely.

As @dlaiocean mentioned, the CDC has come out with a new update on the likely culprit of vaping-related illnesses and deaths: "As of October 22, 2019, a total of 1,604 cases of EVALI, including 34 deaths, were reported to CDC. Based on data collected as of October 15, 2019, use of tetrahydrocannabinol (THC)-containing products in the 3 months preceding symptom onset was reported by 86% of patients." [1]
CNN reportedd "Deaths linked to vaping often involved THC products, not nicotine, CDC says." Increase zero probability.

Juul just voluntarily suspended the sale of fruity-favored e-cigarettes due to the imminent Federal ban of such products (I.e. a partial ban for this question) [1]. This will negate the need for a partial ban from individual states. It will also reduce the argument for a full ban from the states.

Court of Claims suspends MI vaping ban; Gov vows to go to Supreme Court: https://www.wlns.com/news/whitmer-to-seek-supreme-court-ruling-to-keep-vaping-ban/. Maintaining low likelihood of all-out vaping ban.

E-cigarettes have been introduced in the US since 2004 [1]. Currently CDC estimated that there are 6 million vaping users [1]. No illness or death has been attributed to vaping until April 2019. The mortality of this unknown illness is about 2% (about 26 deaths out of 1299 illness) [2]. CDC is currently investigating the cause of this illnesses and death. This sudden outbreak of vaping illnesses and death is intriguing and it points to possible links to recent changes in vaping products. There are indications that suggest chemicals (THC, Vitamin E acetate and others) added to vaping oil are potential causes [2], but it will take time for the CDC investigation to arrive at a conclusion, probably till May next year.

I am making this forecast as I believe that there will be a number of states, most likely those on the East and West Coasts, that will ban the sale of vaping products. I do however believe that only a few states will ban the sale of these products as it has been proven to be the sale of illegal vaping products with vitamin E oils contained in them that are actually the cause of the outbreak of deaths in adolescents. We have never banned the sale of any tobacco products, so I believe that it would not be in the best interest of tobacco corporations who hold a significant foothold in the U.S. government to actually ban these products as they provide a considerable amount of revenue to the industry as well as being a new form of smoking in the future that could change the way people think about nicotine and nicotine products.

- Highly taxed in some states (CA, IL, DC, PA for example.) - Cigarette smoking declining fairly rapidly but 85% of young adults (18-29) have tried e-cigs - Vaping replaces cigarettes - tax revenue needed by States - Ultimately, vaping will be deemed safer than cigarettes (if you fully ban vaping, kids turn to cigarettes and it's the counterfeit vaping cartridges causing the deaths) - Counterfeit flavored vaping products increase, more deaths due to the ban - Retail store owners bringing lawsuits in NY and MA - I think there may be 3 States capable of a full ban based on current fears vs. known facts, 2 have already banned flavors so low likelihood they go full board like MA did - Will we learn much more in the next few months?
